		<a name="top" id="top"></a>
		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Heat pump</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p>A <b>heat pump</b> is a machine or device that moves <a href="/wiki/Heat" title="Heat">heat</a> from one location (the 'source') to another location (the 'sink' or 'heat sink') using <a href="/wiki/Mechanical_work" title="Mechanical work" class="mw-redirect">mechanical work</a>. Most heat pump technology moves heat from a low temperature heat source to a higher temperature heat sink.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> Common examples are food <a href="/wiki/Refrigerator" title="Refrigerator">refrigerators</a> and <a href="/wiki/Freezer" title="Freezer" class="mw-redirect">freezers</a>, <a href="/wiki/Air_conditioner" title="Air conditioner">air conditioners</a>, and reversible-cycle heat pumps for providing <a href="/wiki/Thermal_comfort" title="Thermal comfort">thermal comfort</a>. Heat pumps can also operate in reverse, providing heat.</p>
<p>Heat pumps can be thought of as a <a href="/wiki/Heat_engine" title="Heat engine">heat engine</a> which is operating in reverse. One common type of heat pump works by exploiting the physical properties of an evaporating and <a href="/wiki/Condensation" title="Condensation">condensing</a> fluid known as a <a href="/wiki/Refrigerant" title="Refrigerant">refrigerant</a>. In heating, ventilation, and air conditioning (<a href="/wiki/HVAC" title="HVAC">HVAC</a>) applications, a heat pump normally refers to a <a href="/wiki/Vapor-compression_refrigeration" title="Vapor-compression refrigeration">vapor-compression refrigeration</a> device that includes a <a href="/wiki/Reversing_valve" title="Reversing valve">reversing valve</a> and optimized <a href="/wiki/Heat_exchangers" title="Heat exchangers" class="mw-redirect">heat exchangers</a> so that the direction of heat flow may be reversed. Most commonly, heat pumps draw heat from the air or from the ground. Some air-source heat pumps do not work as well when temperatures fall below around −5°C.</p>
